\begin{abstract}
Current continual learning approaches predominantly assume task similarity, where sequential tasks are typically drawn from related domains or hierarchically structured categories. However, under high task heterogeneity, where tasks exhibit low semantic overlap and divergent input-output structures, these methods suffer from poor forward transfer and rigid capacity allocation. To address this challenge, we propose Task-differentiated Atomic Skill Expansion and Routing (\texttt{TASER}), a framework for highly heterogeneous continual learning that jointly resolves how many atomic skills to add and which ones to use. The framework consists of three core modules: (i) atomic skill incremental learning, which dynamically determines the number of new skills to instantiate per task and trains them incrementally, with the skill count guided by task divergence and model uncertainty; (ii) orthogonality-enhanced skill detection, which preserves atomicity by ensuring each skill remains semantically distinct and independently reusable; and (iii) skill dynamic routing, which selects and composes active skills using lightweight, task-conditioned gating. We evaluate our approach on a benchmark of highly heterogeneous tasks. Results show an XXX improvement in average accuracy over strong baselines and an XXX reduction in backward transfer loss. Code and benchmarks will be publicly available on GitHub.
\keywords{Continual Learning  \and Atomic Skill \and Heterogeneous Tasks.}
\end{abstract}
\section{Introduction}
\label{sec:intro}
Continual learning is a machine learning paradigm in which a model learns from a sequence of tasks over time, updating its parameters incrementally while preserving performance on previously encountered tasks~\cite{yang2025recent}. The core objective is to achieve both stability and plasticity without relying on original training data or full retraining. This setting closely reflects real-world deployment scenarios, where models must continuously adapt to evolving user needs, domain shifts, and open-ended task streams.
Humans naturally possess a remarkable ability to learn continuously throughout their lifespan, acquiring an extensive repertoire of diverse skills—from riding a bicycle to writing complex code—without overwriting previously mastered abilities. Neuroscientific research reveals that this lifelong learning capability is fundamentally driven by \textit{neuroplasticity} and, crucially, \textit{adult neurogenesis}~\cite{placeholder_neurogenesis_1,placeholder_neurogenesis_2}. When faced with novel and complex stimuli, the human brain does not merely adjust existing synaptic weights within a rigidly fixed space. Rather, it structurally adapts by generating new neurons and allocating dedicated, non-overlapping functional modules to encode new experiences. This dynamic expansion of neural resources ensures that newly acquired capabilities have sufficient representational capacity, preventing disruptive interference with consolidated memory networks.
Despite this biological precedent, existing continual learning methods for large language models have primarily been evaluated on benchmarks characterized by low task heterogeneity~\cite{}. Typical setups include sequential fine-tuning on similar datasets, where sequential tasks inherently share linguistic structures, output formats, and underlying reasoning patterns. Approaches such as replay-based methods~\cite{}, elastic weight consolidation~\cite{}, adapter-based parameter isolation~\cite{}, and prompt tuning heavily rely on the assumption that knowledge transfer between adjacent tasks is readily feasible. However, these assumptions break down under high task heterogeneity—for example, when a model must transition from mathematical theorem proving to legal contract summarization, and then to creative story generation. In such scenarios, input distributions, output modalities, evaluation criteria, and functional requirements diverge substantially. Despite its critical practical importance, continual learning across highly heterogeneous tasks remains underrepresented in both theoretical frameworks and standardized evaluation protocols.
Two central challenges emerge in this high-heterogeneity regime. First, large task divergence leads to severe catastrophic forgetting and poor forward transfer. When a model trained on logical deduction encounters a generative storytelling task, gradient updates strongly perturb representations critical for symbolic reasoning, causing rapid performance decay on earlier tasks. Second, skill requirements across diverse tasks are simultaneously divergent and overlapping. Some tasks demand entirely specialized capabilities (e.g., parsing formal logic syntax), while others reuse foundational components (e.g., named entity recognition or clause boundary detection). A fixed architecture cannot support both task-specific specialization and cross-task sharing; conversely, naive expansion strategies either waste capacity or introduce representational interference.
To address these challenges, we propose \textbf{T}ask-differentiated \textbf{A}tomic \textbf{S}kill \textbf{E}xpansion and \textbf{R}outing (\texttt{TASER}), a continual learning framework explicitly designed to handle high task heterogeneity. \texttt{TASER} jointly resolves how many atomic skills to add and which ones to use, built upon three core, interdependent modules. First, \textit{atomic skill incremental learning} dynamically determines the number of new atomic skills to instantiate for each incoming task. This decision is guided by quantifiable signals, including task divergence (measured via embedding distance) and model uncertainty (estimated from calibration scores). New skills are then trained incrementally with bounded capacity and no shared parameters across tasks. Second, \textit{orthogonality-enhanced skill detection} is applied during training to ensure parameter-level separation between all atomic skills. This enforces functional encapsulation and minimizes representational interference, preserving the atomicity and independent reusability of each skill. Third, \textit{skill dynamic routing} implements a lightweight, task-conditioned gating mechanism that selects and composes active skills at inference time. The gating weights are computed solely from the task identity representation, ensuring a deterministic, interpretable, and zero-shot usable composition.
Our main contributions are summarized as follows:
\begin{itemize}[leftmargin=*, align=left]
\item We define and operationalize continual learning under high task heterogeneity. To this end, we provide a clear problem formulation, measurable criteria for task divergence, and a reproducible benchmark comprising 12 functionally distinct tasks spanning logical reasoning, domain-specific QA, and generative domains.
\item We introduce \texttt{TASER}, a novel framework featuring atomic skill incremental learning and orthogonality-enhanced skill detection. This protocol jointly governs skill count, initialization, and parameter isolation in a highly task-aware manner.
\item We demonstrate through extensive experiments that \texttt{TASER} achieves an XXX improvement in average accuracy over state-of-the-art continual learning baselines, reduces backward transfer loss by XXX, and improves forward transfer robustness by XXX. These results validate that explicit, task-structured capacity growth is essential for continual adaptation across highly heterogeneous task sequences.
\end{itemize}
