\section{Method}
\label{sec:method}

\subsection{Overview}
\label{sec:method_overview}
To tackle continual learning under \emph{high task heterogeneity}---where sequential tasks exhibit low semantic overlap, divergent input--output structures, and consequently weak natural transfer---we propose \textbf{T}ask-differentiated \textbf{A}tomic \textbf{S}kill \textbf{E}xpansion and \textbf{R}outing (\texttt{TASER}). \texttt{TASER} organizes model capacity into a growing set of \emph{atomic skills} (small, reusable functional modules) and jointly answers two coupled questions for each incoming task: (i) \emph{how many new skills to add}, and (ii) \emph{which skills to activate and how to compose them at inference time}. The framework consists of three coordinated components: (1) \textbf{Atomic Skill Incremental Learning}, which adaptively instantiates and trains a task-specific number of new skills guided by measurable signals such as task divergence and model uncertainty; (2) \textbf{Orthogonality-enhanced Skill Detection}, which enforces separation among skills during training (e.g., via orthogonality/disentanglement constraints) to preserve skill \emph{atomicity} and reduce interference; and (3) \textbf{Skill Dynamic Routing}, which employs a lightweight, task-conditioned gating mechanism to select and combine a sparse subset of skills for prediction, balancing task-specific specialization and cross-task reuse without retraining the entire model.

\subsection{Task Definition: Highly Heterogeneous Continual Learning}
\label{sec:task_definition}
We consider a sequential task stream
\begin{equation}
\{\mathcal{T}_1, \mathcal{T}_2, \ldots, \mathcal{T}_K\},
\end{equation}
where each task is defined as
\begin{equation}
\mathcal{T}_k = \langle \mathcal{D}_k, \mathcal{Y}_k, \mathcal{L}_k \rangle.
\end{equation}
Here, $\mathcal{D}_k$ denotes the task-specific data distribution (or dataset) over an input space $\mathcal{X}_k$, $\mathcal{Y}_k$ denotes the output space/structure (e.g., class labels, extractive spans, structured outputs, or free-form text), and $\mathcal{L}_k$ is the learning objective (loss or evaluation criterion). At time step $k$, the learner observes training samples from the current task only, i.e.,
\begin{equation}
\mathcal{S}_k = \{(x_i^{(k)}, y_i^{(k)})\}_{i=1}^{n_k} \sim \mathcal{D}_k,
\end{equation}
and updates its parameters without full retraining and without access to raw data from prior tasks (unless explicitly allowed in a constrained form).

Let $f_{\theta_k}$ be the model after learning task $\mathcal{T}_k$. The continual learning objective is to achieve strong performance on the current task while retaining performance on all previously seen tasks:
\begin{equation}
\min_{\theta_k}\;\; \sum_{j=1}^{k} \mathbb{E}_{(x,y)\sim \mathcal{D}_j}\big[\mathcal{L}_j\big(f_{\theta_k}(x), y\big)\big],
\end{equation}
subject to the sequential data access constraint (training proceeds in the order $1\!\rightarrow\!2\!\rightarrow\!\cdots\!\rightarrow\!K$ and only $\mathcal{S}_k$ is available at step $k$).

Unlike conventional continual learning, we focus on the \emph{high-heterogeneity} regime, where tasks may differ simultaneously in domain, reasoning demands, and input--output format. We operationalize heterogeneity via a task divergence measure
\begin{equation}
d(\mathcal{T}_i, \mathcal{T}_j),
\end{equation}
for example computed as a distance between task representations derived from task descriptions and/or example embeddings. High divergence (large $d$) indicates low semantic overlap and structural mismatch, which amplifies catastrophic forgetting and weakens forward transfer, motivating \texttt{TASER}'s task-differentiated expansion and routing.
